BEGIN_PGML
A shirt is on sale for [`20\%`] off. The sale price is [`\$51.00\text{.}`] What was the shirt's original price?

[_]{$cost}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Let [`x`] represent the original price of the shirt. Since [`20\%`] is removed to bring the cost down to [`\$51\text{,}`] we can set up the equation:

[```\newcommand{\pinover}[2]{\overset{\overset{\mathrm{\ #2\ }}{|}}{\strut #1 \strut}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
\pinover{x}{original}\pinover{-}{minus}\pinover{0.20}{20\%}\pinover{\cdot}{of}\pinover{x}{original}\amp\pinover{=}{is}\pinover{51}{\$51}
\end{aligned}
```]

Now we have the skills to solve this equation.

[```\newcommand{\divideunder}[2]{\frac{#1}{{\highlight{{#2}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
x - 0.20x \amp= 51\\
0.80x \amp= 51\\
\divideunder{0.80x}{0.80}\amp=\divideunder{51}{0.80}\\
x\amp=63.75
\end{aligned}
```]

The shirt's original price was [`\$63.75\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

